Trump and the Economy
New York—Financial markets finally woke up to the reality that Trump is the U.S. president.
The world has endured two years of unfiltered tweets and public remarks from this most powerful person on the globe, and the obvious question is, what has kept this going for so long?
On the one hand, until now, investors have believed that Trump only made noise but never delivered results.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies favorable to the corporate sector and shareholders, they are willing to give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many believe that in the end, the "adults in the room" will rein in Trump and ensure that government policies stay within bounds.
Such assumptions were more or less confirmed during Trump's first year in office, a period when economic growth and expectations of corporate profit growth—thanks to the impending tax cuts and deregulation—resulted in a standout stock market performance.
In 2017, U.S. stock indices rose more than 20%.
But in 2018, the situation took a sharp turn for the worse, especially in the final months.
Although corporate profits rose by more than 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the U.S. stock market fluctuated throughout most of the year and is now sharply declining.
Currently, various indices are in correction territory (i.e., down 10% from recent highs), and technology stock indices (such as the Nasdaq) have fallen into a bear market (a decline of 20% or more).
Although increased financial market volatility reflects concerns over China, Italy, and other Eurozone economies, as well as key emerging markets, the recent turmoil is due to Trump.
At the start of the year, Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, which pushed up long-term interest rates and brought an economy already nearing full employment to a climax.
By February, concerns that inflation would rise above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% led to the first wave of risk aversion in 2018.
Following that, Trump launched a trade war against China and other key U.S. trading partners.
Concerns over government protectionist policies have fluctuated throughout the year, but are now reaching new highs.
Recent U.S. actions toward China appear to be preparing for a comprehensive trade, economic, and geopolitical cold war.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies could lead to stagflation (weakened growth coupled with increased inflation).
After all, Trump prepared to restrict foreign direct investment and implemented broad immigration restrictions, which will hinder the growth of the labor supply amid increasingly severe issues of an aging workforce and skill mismatches.
Furthermore, the Trump administration has yet to propose an infrastructure plan to stimulate private sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy.
On Twitter and other occasions, Trump continuously criticized corporate hiring, production, investment, and pricing practices, especially those of technology companies, which already face widespread opposition and increasingly fierce competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets were also impacted by U.S. policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening pushed up short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies experienced capital flight and an increase in the value of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies heavily reliant on exports suffered losses due to falling commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade ties to China felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy created volatility.
The U.S. reinstatement of sanctions against Iran drove up oil prices, and subsequently, the U.S. government revoked exemptions and pressured Saudi Arabia to increase oil production, leading to a sharp decline in oil prices.
Although U.S. consumers benefited from low oil prices, the stock prices of U.S. energy companies could not hold up.
In addition, excessive oil price volatility is detrimental to both producers and consumers, as it hinders sound investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, it is now evident that the benefits of last year's tax cuts have largely flowed to the corporate sector, rather than to households in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages.
This suggests that household consumption may soon slow down, further affecting the economy.
However, the main reason for the recent sharp decline in U.S. and global stock markets over the last quarter has been Trump's own statements and actions.
Worse than the prominent risk of a full-scale trade war with China (despite his recent "ceasefire" agreement with Chinese President Xi Jinping) is Trump's public criticism of the Federal Reserve. His criticism began in spring 2018, when the U.S. economic growth rate exceeded 4%.
Because of these earlier criticisms, the markets became jittery when the Federal Reserve correctly decided to raise interest rates this month, while hinting at a slower pace of rate hikes in 2019.
More likely, the Federal Reserve's relatively hawkish stance was a response to Trump's criticisms of it.
Faced with hostile tweets from the president, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell needed to signal that the central bank still maintained political independence.
But then, after Congress refused to fund his useless Mexico border wall, Trump decided to shut down part of the federal government.
This move pushed the market into a near-panic state, and soon after the government shutdown, reports emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell — which could turn a market correction into a crash.
On the eve of the Christmas holiday, U.S. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to make a public statement to calm the markets.
He claimed that Trump had no plan to fire Powell and that the U.S. fiscal condition was sound — which only highlighted the question of whether the situation was truly sound.
Recent internal government personnel changes that may not affect economic decisions have also caused concern in the markets.
White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are about to leave, and Trump's cabinet will have no sane people left.
What will remain are all economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks, following Trump's lead.
The possibility of a comprehensive geopolitical conflict with China remains excluded neither.
A new cold war is highly likely to lead to deglobalization and disrupt global supply chains, but the technology sector will be the first to suffer, as evidenced by recent cases involving ZTE and Huawei.
At the same time, Trump seems determined to undermine the cohesion of the EU and NATO amid economic and political instability in Europe.
The investigation by special counsel Robert Mueller into the relationship between Trump's 2016 campaign and Russia has been the Damoclean sword hanging over Trump's presidency.
Trump is now the Dr. Strangelove of financial markets.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is trapped in a mutually assured economic destruction from which he cannot extricate himself.
Today, the markets are seeing this danger, with the risks of a financial crisis and global recession rising sharply.
